  "text": "The ideal management of this complication remains uncertain although much progress has already been made [CITATION_1] . Ideally, the diagnosis should be made antenatally by medical imaging for women at high risk, which enables health care providers to plan the delivery more effectively and reduce morbidity. Unfortunately, in many cases, especially during the first or second trimester, diagnosis is made only on account of the unusual resistance of the placenta to detachment when attempting a uterine revision [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
